form.preferredDefinition: The individual is asked to complete a series of questions about his or her feelings about physical activities and how sure he or she is that he or she will perform physical activities under certain circumstances. The questionnaire includes other questions about how much support the individual receives from family members and friends to participate in physical activity or sports. Almost all the items have five response options in a Likert-type scale with values of 1-5 (e.g., never = 1, many times = 5).

question.questionText: Physical Activity Change Strategies The following are activities, thoughts, and feelings people use to help them change their physical activity. Think of any similar experiences you may be having or have had in the past month. Then rate HOW OFTEN you do each of the following: (strategies_151303)
I look for information about physical activity or sports. (physicalactivity_selfefficacy_changestrategies_1)
I keep track of how much physical activity I do. (physicalactivity_selfefficacy_changestrategies_2)
I find ways to get around the things that get in the way of being physically active. (physicalactivity_selfefficacy_changestrategies_3)

I think about how my surroundings affect the amount of physical activity I do. (Surroundings are things like having exercise equipment at home or a park nearby.) (physicalactivity_selfefficacy_changestrategies_4)
I put reminders around my home to be physically active. (physicalactivity_selfefficacy_changestrategies_5)
I reward myself for being physically active. (physicalactivity_selfefficacy_changestrategies_6)
I do things to make physical activity more enjoyable. (physicalactivity_selfefficacy_changestrategies_7)
I think about the benefits I will get from being physically active. (physicalactivity_selfefficacy_changestrategies_8)
I try to think more about the benefits of physical activity and less about the hassles of being active. (physicalactivity_selfefficacy_changestrategies_9)
I say positive things to myself about physical activity. (physicalactivity_selfefficacy_changestrategies_10)
When I get off track with my physical activity plans, I tell myself I can start again and get right back on track. (physicalactivity_selfefficacy_changestrategies_11)
I have a friend or family member who encourages me to do physical activity. (physicalactivity_selfefficacy_changestrategies_12)
I try different kinds of physical activity so that I have more options to choose from. (physicalactivity_selfefficacy_changestrategies_13)
I set goals to do physical activity. (physicalactivity_selfefficacy_changestrategies_14)
I make backup plans to be sure I get my physical activity. (physicalactivity_selfefficacy_changestrategies_15)
Physical Activity Pros & Cons The following statements are different beliefs about physical activity. (prosandcons_151303)

HOW IMPORTANT IS EACH STATEMENT TO YOU WHEN DECIDING WHETHER OR NOT TO DO PHYSICAL ACTIVITY? I would feel embarrassed if people saw me doing physical activity. (physicalactivity_selfefficacy_physicalactivity_proscons_1)
HOW IMPORTANT IS EACH STATEMENT TO YOU WHEN DECIDING WHETHER OR NOT TO DO PHYSICAL ACTIVITY? Physical activity would help me stay fit. (physicalactivity_selfefficacy_physicalactivity_proscons_2)

HOW IMPORTANT IS EACH STATEMENT TO YOU WHEN DECIDING WHETHER OR NOT TO DO PHYSICAL ACTIVITY? My parents would be happy if I did physical activity. (physicalactivity_selfefficacy_physicalactivity_proscons_3)

HOW IMPORTANT IS EACH STATEMENT TO YOU WHEN DECIDING WHETHER OR NOT TO DO PHYSICAL ACTIVITY? There is too much I would have to learn to do physical activity. (physicalactivity_selfefficacy_physicalactivity_proscons_4)

HOW IMPORTANT IS EACH STATEMENT TO YOU WHEN DECIDING WHETHER OR NOT TO DO PHYSICAL ACTIVITY? I would feel better about myself if I did physical activity. (physicalactivity_selfefficacy_physicalactivity_proscons_5)

HOW IMPORTANT IS EACH STATEMENT TO YOU WHEN DECIDING WHETHER OR NOT TO DO PHYSICAL ACTIVITY? I would need too much help from my parents to do physical activity. (physicalactivity_selfefficacy_physicalactivity_proscons_6)

HOW IMPORTANT IS EACH STATEMENT TO YOU WHEN DECIDING WHETHER OR NOT TO DO PHYSICAL ACTIVITY? I do not like the way physical activity and exercise makes me feel. (physicalactivity_selfefficacy_physicalactivity_proscons_7)

HOW IMPORTANT IS EACH STATEMENT TO YOU WHEN DECIDING WHETHER OR NOT TO DO PHYSICAL ACTIVITY? I would have fun doing physical activity or playing sports with my friends. (physicalactivity_selfefficacy_physicalactivity_proscons_8)

HOW IMPORTANT IS EACH STATEMENT TO YOU WHEN DECIDING WHETHER OR NOT TO DO PHYSICAL ACTIVITY? I would have more energy if I did physical activity. (physicalactivity_selfefficacy_physicalactivity_proscons_9)

HOW IMPORTANT IS EACH STATEMENT TO YOU WHEN DECIDING WHETHER OR NOT TO DO PHYSICAL ACTIVITY? Physical activity takes time away from being with my friends. (physicalactivity_selfefficacy_physicalactivity_proscons_10)

During a typical week, how often has a member of your household: (For example, your father, mother, brother, sister, grandparent, or other relatives) Watched you participate in physical activity or play sports? (physicalactivity_selfefficacy_familysupport_1)

form.longName: PhenX PX160201 - Assay For Cytokine Panel 12
form.preferredDefinition: This protocol provides instructions for drawing, processing, and storing blood according to the National Health and Nutrition Examination Survey (NHANES) and uses the multi-analyte fluorescent detection (MAFD) method to measure 12¿different cytokines: Interferon gamma (IFN-gamma), Interleukin-1 beta (IL-1 beta), Interleukin-10 (IL-10), Interleukin-12 (IL-12), Interleukin-13 (IL-13), Interleukin-2 (IL-2), Interleukin-2 Receptor (IL-2R), Interleukin-4 (IL-4), Interleukin-5 (IL-5), Interleukin-6 (IL-6), Interleukin-8 (IL-8), Tumor Necrosis Factor alpha (TNF alpha).

question.questionText: Persons will be excluded from this component if they: report that they have hemophilia, or report that they have received cancer chemotherapy in the last 4 weeks. SP = Sample Person WG recommends that the investigator record whether the blood was drawn and whether the full amount was obtained. Process the Sample for the SerumEditor's Note: Please review chapter 8 of the Laboratory Procedures Manual from the NHANES 20072008 for a full description of Blood Processing procedures: 20072008 NHANES Lab Manual. Allow the blood to clot by setting aside for 3045 minutes at room temperature. Do not clot for more than 1 hour. Centrifuge the tube at room temperature to separate the serum and aliquot into an appropriate storage tube. Determine if the serum is hemolyzed, turbid, lipemic, or icteric. If so, enter a comment to describe the plasma. Laboratory Assay for Cytokine Panel 12 The Infectious Diseases and Immunity WG recommend the multianalyte fluorescent detection (MAFD) method of Cytokine Panel 12 offered through ARUP Laboratories. To aid comparability, the Infectious Diseases and Immunity WG recommends that the investigator record the make and manufacturer of equipment used and the repeatability and coefficients of variation for the assay. (desc1_160201)
Do you have hemophilia? (exclusion from Phlebotomy) (hemophilia)

Venipuncture Procedures Editor's Note: Please review chapter 4 of the Laboratory Procedures Manual from the NHANES for a full description of phlebotomy procedures: 2007-2008 NHANES Lab Manual. Venipuncture should generally be performed using the median cubital, cephalic, or basilica veins in the left arm unless this arm is unsuitable. If the veins in the left arm are unsuitable, look for suitable veins on the right arm. If the veins in the antecubital space on both arms are not suitable, then look for veins in the forearm or dorsal side of the hand on the left arm/hand and then right arm/hand. The Infectious Diseases and Immunity WG recommends that 3 mL serum be collected from each participant. Recording the Results of the Venipuncture Procedure Immediately after completing the venipuncture, record the results of the blood draw, the reasons for a tube not being drawn according to the protocol, and any comments about the venipuncture. Note from the Infectious Diseases and Immunity WG: The Infectious Diseases and Immunity WG recommends that the investigator record whether the blood was drawn and whether the full amount was obtained. Process the Sample for the Serum Editor's Note: Please review chapter 8 of the Laboratory Procedures Manual from the NHANES 2007-2008 for a full description of Blood Processing procedures: 2007-2008 NHANES Lab Manual. Allow the blood to clot by setting aside for 30-45 minutes at room temperature. Do not clot for more than 1 hour. Centrifuge the tube at room temperature to separate the serum and aliquot into an appropriate storage tube. Determine if the serum is hemolyzed, turbid, lipemic, or icteric. If so, enter a comment to describe the plasma. form.longName: PhenX PX160101 - Assay For Chlamydia Gonorrhea
form.preferredDefinition: This protocol provides basic instructions for collecting and processing urine according to National Health and Nutrition Examination Survey (NHANES) methods for assessing the presence of Chlamydia trachomatis and/or Neisseria gonorrhoeae, sexually transmitted bacterial diseases. Strand Displacement Amplification Assay is the method used.

headerInstruction.text: The following is a summary version of the full National Health and Nutrition Examination Survey (NHANES) 20072008 protocol.

question.questionText: Editor's Note: Please review chapter 5 of the Laboratory Procedures Manual from the NHANES 20072008 for a full description of urine collection and processing procedures: 20072008 NHANES Lab Manual. The coordinator explains the following instructions to the subject before urine collection: Wash hands with soap and water. It is important that the cup and cap not touch or come into contact with any parts of the body, clothing, or external surfaces. Close container to minimize exposure to air. Refrigerate all insufficient urine samples. When additional urine is obtained, pool the urine, mix, and process. (px060101_instr2)

form.longName: PhenX PX151401 - Cardiorespiratory Fitness Nonexercise Test Estimate
form.preferredDefinition: Cardiorespiratory fitness is estimated from a non-exercise test model that includes gender, age, body mass index, resting heart rate, and self-reported physical activity. Capture this information via standard methods, and add the values to Jurca and colleagues' (2005) worksheet. Follow the equation in the worksheet to determine the maximal metabolic equivalent level.

headerInstruction.text: Measure and record the following information about the participant.

question.questionText: Participant's age (years) (pxt151401_age)
Participant's height (centimeters) (height)
Participant's weight (kilograms) (pxt151401_weight)
Participant's body mass index (BMI) in kilograms per meter2 BMI = (weight in lbs X 703)/(height in inches)2 or (weight in kilograms)/(height in meters)2 (bmi)

instruction.text: datatype=number; UOM=(weight in kilogram)/(height in meter)2

question.questionText: Resting heart rate (HR) measured HR from person's wrist pulse after 5 minutes of rest in the supine position (resting_heart_rate)

Administer the questions from the fivecategory physical activity scale, found in Step 1 of the worksheet of Jurca et al. (2005). Add age, height, weight, and so forth to the equation in Step 2 of the worksheet to calculate the estimated MET value. Jurca, R., Jackson, A. S., LaMonte, M. J., Morrow, J. R., Blair, S. N., Wareham, N. J., Haskell, W. L., van Mechelen, W., Church, T. S., Jakicic, J. M., and Laukkanen, R. (2005). Assessing cardiorespiratory fitness without performing exercise testing. American Journal of Preventive Medicine, 29(3), 185193. (inst2151401)
